span class=title> World Court</span><hr size=1>      Been hearing about it a lot about it latley and was just curious of some opinions on it. I honestly know little about it but, from what I have heard I really don't care too much for it. My information could be incorrect but, it might not be. <p><img src=http://eshamlin.home.mindspring.com/lith.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umaeri.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maeri</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 409<br> <font color=#E9D756>(4/21/02 5:10:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=295.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: World Court</span><hr size=1> The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.icj-cij.org">International Court of Justice</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is the UN body (established in 1946) to settle legal disputed between countries.<br>
<br>
The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.un.org/law/icc">International Criminal Court</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is a propsed body basically to replace the ad hoc War Crimes Tribunals that are set up from time to time. It's charter deals with <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.un.org/law/icc/statute/elements/english/1_add2e.pdf">genocide, crimes against humanity, and war crimes</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->(pdf), and is directed at crimes of individuals (as opposed to the ICJ which deals with states). It will only deal with such cases when the country in question is unwilling or unable to do so.  There's <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.un.org/law/icc/general/overview.htm">an overview</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> of it's reason's for creation at the UN web site.<br>
<br>
From <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.hrw.org/campaigns/icc/">Human Rights Watch</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The Statute outlining the creation of the court was adopted at an international conference in Rome on July 17, 1998. After 5 weeks of intense negotiations, 120 countries voted to adopt the treaty. Only seven countries voted against it (including China, Israel, Iraq, and the United States) and 21 abstained. Before the Court can be set up, 60 countries need to ratify the treaty. 139 states signed the treaty by the 31 December 2000 deadline. As of April 11, 2002, 66 countries have ratified it. The tribunal will come into force on July 1, 2002.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There's a good <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.hrw.org/campaigns/icc/qna.htm">Q&amp;A over there too.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Clinton ended up signing the treaty, but the US has not ratified it, meaning that the court would not hold juristiction over US citizens, and the US would have no say in the appointment of judges, adminstrative or funding issues for the court. Bush is considering removing the signature from the treaty entirely. Libya is the other country still actively speaking out against the court. <p>----------------------------------<br>
[58 Troubadour]
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=78662">Maeri</a>
&lt;Anlah'Shok&gt;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umartigan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Martigan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1040<br> <font color=#E9D756>(5/6/02 11:44:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=295.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: World Court</span><hr size=1> Picture the possibility of US soldiers being prosecuted in a World Court for "crimes" that would not be considered so under the US Constitution... hey, it's a possibility.<br>
<br>
I don't go for anything that could possibly undermine our Constitution. This may not at first, but it's a step in that direction. <p><img src=http://www.garlic.com/~hypatia/images/staff.gif width=460 height=40><br>
