<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  In a communication received on 6 May 2002, the Government of the United States of America informed the Secretary-General of the following:<br>
<br>
&quot;This is to inform you, in connection with the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court adopted on July 17, 1998, that the United States does not intend to become a party to the treaty. Accordingly, the United States has no legal obligations arising from its signature on December 31, 2000. The United States requests that its intention not become a party, as expressed in this letter, be reflected in the depositary's status lists relating to this treaty.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The court has a very well defined set of crimes it can prosecute for. Have a look at EzCode Parsing Error:=]the pdf document[ I indicated earlier. I doubt there's anything in there which would be considered legal under US law. I wouldn't be prepared to declare blind faith in a consitution or set of laws which regards any of the activities defined as crimes under the Rome Statue as OK.<br>
<br>
If you are worried about possible changes (&quot;This may not at first, but it's a step in that direction&quot;), again, look at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://Thismaynotatfirst,butit'sastepinthatdirection">the statue itself</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Article 121 deals with amendments to the statue. Only states party to the statue can propose amendments (the US has thereby ruled itself out of any input into the operations of the court). A 2/3 majority of states is required to adopt and amendment. A 7/8 majority must ratify the amendment for it to go into force. For a change to articles 5-8 (which define the crimes covered by the court), even if it has been ratified by 7/8 of the parties, the court will not exercise juristiction over states which have not accepted the amendment. Finally, if an amendment is accepted, a state not agreeing to the amendment can withdraw  from the entire statute. That enough safeguards for you? <p>----------------------------------<br>
[58 Troubadour]
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=78662">Maeri</a>
